JOHANNESBURG - The South African Weather Service (SAWS) on Wednesday said the unusual rainfall, known as La Niña, is expected to cause more disruptive rain for the rest of the summer and into autumn. Persistent rainfall in Gauteng in the last few weeks has left the Vaal Dam now over 110% full, while other parts of the country like the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal experience flooding. WATCH: Ladysmith flooded after heavy rainfall  The Department of Cooperative Governance said so far, 82 people have died in drowning and lightning incidents across the country this season. “We are currently in a La Niña, which means for our summer rainfall region, we are expecting above-normal rainfall. So, this forecast has been in play already. Last year, our seasonal forecasters were seeing the signals for our summer season. So, as we’ve seen, it has happened,” explained forecaster, Elizabeth Viljoen.